{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522560"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:46:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:46:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13838"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13838"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.17,0.23,0.36,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6455"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107874"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6455"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13838"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90290"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1783"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12763"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12764"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40054"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42945"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107874"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of scaly, red patches on his elbows, knees, and scalp. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He recently purchased an outdoor spa four months prior, and denies any similar rashes in the past. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are well-demarcated, erythematous plaques with silvery scales covering approximately 5% of his body surface area. The lesions are mildly pruritic but not painful. No joint swelling or tenderness is noted. He has tried topical calcipotriol and betamethasone combination for six weeks with minimal improvement and is looking for further management options.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adalimumab injections","Oral acitretin","Topical tacrolimus","Narrowband UVB phototherapy","Oral methotrexate"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with mild to moderate plaque \u003Cstrong\u003Epsoriasis\u003C/strong\u003E that has not responded adequately to first-line topical therapy. The peak onset can be either 15\u201325 years and 50\u201360 years, and it has a genetic link. The most appropriate next step in management is \u003Cstrong\u003Enarrowband UVB phototherapy\u003C/strong\u003E. This treatment is often considered when topical treatments have failed but before moving to systemic therapies, especially in cases of mild to moderate psoriasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpa pool folliculitis (pseudomonas folliculitis) presents with more red papules or nodules rather than plaques as shown for this case. It would be a consideration for a patient with new spa and new rash, however in this case it was just unfortunate timing. The silvery scale appearance is more typically of psoriasis and the rash distribution is also congruent with psoriasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral methotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E is a systemic treatment typically reserved for more severe cases of psoriasis or when topical treatments and phototherapy have failed. While it could be considered if phototherapy is unsuccessful, it would be premature at this stage given the limited body surface area involvement and the availability of less aggressive options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical tacrolimus\u003C/strong\u003E is sometimes used for psoriasis, particularly in sensitive areas like the face or genitals. However, it\u0027s not typically more effective than the calcipotriol and betamethasone combination that the patient has already tried, and thus is unlikely to provide significant additional benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral acitretin\u003C/strong\u003E is a systemic retinoid that can be effective for psoriasis, but it\u0027s associated with significant side effects and is typically used for more severe cases or specific types of psoriasis (like pustular psoriasis). It would be overly aggressive at this stage of treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdalimumab\u003C/strong\u003E is a TNF-alpha inhibitor biologic therapy used for severe psoriasis that hasn\u0027t responded to other systemic treatments. It would be inappropriate at this stage for a patient with mild to moderate disease who has only tried topical therapy. Other biological agents for treatment of severe psoriasis are the interluekin 17 inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENarrowband UVB phototherapy has been shown to be effective and safe for psoriasis. It works by suppressing T cell function in the skin and inducing apoptosis of activated T cells. While it requires multiple treatments over several weeks which can be difficult for patients, it has a good safety profile without systemic side effects and can lead to significant improvement in psoriasis symptoms. If phototherapy is unsuccessful, then systemic treatments like methotrexate might be considered as the next step or used together with biological agents.   Encouraging good sleep hygiene, frequent moisturising with ointments and quitting smoking if appropriate also assist in decreasing symptoms. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Narrowband UVB phototherapy is an effective second-line treatment for mild to moderate plaque psoriasis when topical treatments have failed.","Systemic treatments like methotrexate are reserved for moderate to severe psoriasis or when topical and phototherapy treatments have failed."],"references":["Jones C, Gupta M, Uddin S, Oakley A, Coulson I. Psoriasis. In: DermnetNZ. 2023. Available in: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/psoriasis","Zhang P, Wu M. A Clinical review of phototherapy for psoriasis. Lasers Medical Science. 2018; 33 (1): 173- 180.  Available in: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5756569/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90290"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13838"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90290"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-04T00:55:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-04T00:56:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6455"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107874"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id"